        <h1>LeetCode 3432: Count Partitions with Even Sum Difference (C++)</h1>
        <div class="problem-description">
            <p><strong>Problem:</strong>
                You are given a 0-indexed integer array nums of length n. The number of ways to partition nums is the
                number
                of indices i where 0 <= i < n - 1 such that the absolute difference between the sum of the first i + 1
                    elements and the sum of the remaining elements is even. Return the number of ways to partition nums
                    to satisfy this condition. The key insight is that if the total sum is even, then for any partition,
                    the difference between left and right sums will be even. If the total sum is odd, no valid partition
                    exists. </p>
                    <p><strong>Example:</strong>
                        Input: nums = [1,2,3,4] → Output: 3. Total sum is 10 (even). Valid partitions at indices 0, 1, 2
                        all give
                        even differences.
                        Input: nums = [1,2,3] → Output: 0. Total sum is 6 (even), but we need to check... Actually wait,
                        total is 6,
                        so answer should be 2 (n-1 = 2).
                        Input: nums = [10,10,10,10] → Output: 3. Total is 40 (even), so all n-1 = 3 partitions work.
                    </p>
        </div>
        <div class="code-container">
            <button class="copy-button" onclick="copyCode(this)">Copy Code</button>
            <pre><code class="language-cpp">class Solution {
public:
    int countPartitions(vector&lt;int&gt;&amp; nums) {
        int total = 0;
        for (int v : nums) total += v;
        
        // Only total parity matters
        return (total % 2 == 0) ? (nums.size() - 1) : 0;
    }
};</code></pre>
